description: From Late Latin primagium. (The French word post-dates the English.)

entries.meaning: (archaic) A payment made for loading or unloading a ship, or for care of goods during transit by ship.
examples: By the bill of lading the maſter undertakes to deliver the goods on payment of freight with primage and average accuſtomed.

entries.meaning: (archaic, UK) An import duty levied by a guild of harbour pilots (especially at Kingston-upon-Hull and Newcastle-upon-Tyne).
(Australia, New Zealand) An additional import duty levied by customs.
examples: The rate of primage duty was subsequently increased to 4 per cent. as from the 6th November, 1930.

entries.meaning: (engineering, rare) Droplets of water suspended in steam (especially in the cylinder of a steam engine).
examples: Of these temperatures, only one, the second, indicates primage; all others exhibit a slight superheat.
